# Module Contracts layout

Use this structure in every `{Module}.Contracts` project (e.g. `Invoria.Ordering.Contracts`).

## Bounded context root

Group types by domain area under a context folder (e.g. `Orders/`, `Products/`, `PurchaseOrders/`). Each context has four subfolders:

| Subfolder | Contents | Namespace suffix |
|-----------|----------|-------------------|
| `Enums/` | Shared enums for that context | `.{Context}.Enums` |
| `Dtos/` | API/query/command response shapes | `.{Context}.Dtos` |
| `Events/` | Integration events (Rebus messages) | `.{Context}.Events` |
| `Models/` | Nested payloads on events or cross-module messages (not full API DTOs) | `.{Context}.Models` |

**Example (Ordering):**

```
Ordering.Contracts/
  AssemblyReference.cs
  Orders/
    Enums/       → Invoria.Ordering.Contracts.Orders.Enums
    Dtos/        → Invoria.Ordering.Contracts.Orders.Dtos
    Events/      → Invoria.Ordering.Contracts.Orders.Events
    Models/      → Invoria.Ordering.Contracts.Orders.Models
```

Full namespace: `Invoria.{Module}.Contracts.{Context}.{Enums|Dtos|Events|Models}`.

## Rules

- Keep only `AssemblyReference.cs` (and similar markers) at the contracts project root—no flat `Dtos/`, `Events/`, or `Models/` at root when a context folder exists.
- Put enums in `Enums/`, not under `Events/` (even if only used by one event).
- Folder path must match namespace; update all consumers when moving types.
- New modules: adopt this layout from the first contract type; do not introduce legacy flat folders.

## Cross-module references

Other modules reference contract namespaces explicitly (e.g. `using Invoria.Ordering.Contracts.Orders.Events`). Register Rebus handlers and map assemblies using the contracts project’s `AssemblyReference`.
